  "prompt": "What is the proof for triangular law of vectors?",
  "response": "The triangular law of vectors states that if two vectors, \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) and \\(\\mathbf{B}\\), are represented as two sides of a triangle, then their resultant vector \\(\\mathbf{R}\\) can be represented as the third side of the triangle. Mathematically, it is expressed as:\n\n\\[\n\\mathbf{R} = \\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B}\n\\]\n\nTo prove this law geometrically, we can use the following steps:\n\n### Step 1: Establish the Vectors\nLet \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) and \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) be two vectors initiated from the same point \\(O\\). We will place them such that \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) is positioned starting at point \\(O\\) and terminating at point \\(A\\), while \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) starts at point \\(A\\) and ends at point \\(B\\).\n\n### Step 2: Form the Triangle\nFrom the point \\(O\\), draw the vector \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) to point \\(A\\). Next, from point \\(A\\), draw vector \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) to point \\(B\\). Now, we can observe that the position of point \\(B\\) relative to point \\(O\\) can also be represented by a vector originating from \\(O\\) and terminating at \\(B\\).\n\n### Step 3: Resultant Vector\nThe vector \\(\\mathbf{R}\\), which represents the resultant vector \\( \\mathbf{R} = \\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B} \\), can be drawn directly from the initial point \\(O\\) to the endpoint \\(B\\). The line segment \\(OB\\) represents this resultant vector.\n\n### Step 4: Closure of the Triangle\nWe can mathematically express the relationship using the construction:\n1. Start from point \\(O\\) and go to point \\(A\\) by vector \\(\\mathbf{A}\\).\n2. From point \\(A\\) to point \\(B\\) by vector \\(\\mathbf{B}\\).\n3. We can express the relation: \\(OB = OA + AB\\).\n\nThus, in terms of vectors:\n\\[\n\\mathbf{R} = \\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B}\n\\]\n\n### Step 5: Vector Addition\nIn order to better understand the resulting vector, remember that vector addition can be classified under the parallelogram law, which establishes that the addition of two vectors can be represented as the diagonal of the parallelogram formed by these two vectors. However, as requested proof of the triangular law, we have shown that vector addition leads to a resultant that corresponds to the closure of the triangle.\n\n### Conclusion\nThus, from the geometric construction, we conclude that the triangular law of vector addition indeed holds true, demonstrating equivalently that the resultant vector from adding the two vectors completes the triangle configuration. \n\nThis proof confirms that for any vectors \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) and \\(\\mathbf{B}\\), the resultant \\(\\mathbf{R}\\) can always be represented geometrically by the third side of a triangle formed by connecting the head and tail of the vectors.",
